		<myteasetext>The Inhabited World By David Long A ghost tale, beautifully considered, in which the protagonist inspects the ruins of his life (Houghton Mifflin, $23).</myteasetext>
		<mybyline></mybyline>

		<myarticledate>2006/07/30</myarticledate>
		<myarticlebody>&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The Inhabited World&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;By David Long &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A ghost tale, beautifully considered, in which the protagonist inspects the ruins of his life (Houghton Mifflin, $23).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Strangers in the House: Life Stories&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;By Dorothy Gallagher&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Stories based in actual experience become crafted and illustrated works of art (Random House, $22.95).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The Defining Moment: FDR's Hundred Days and the Triumph of Hope&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;By Jonathan Alter &lt;/em&gt;A keen-eyed portrait of a leader whose restraint protected democracy (Simon &amp;amp; Schuster&lt;em&gt;, &lt;/em&gt;$29.95).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Tomorrow They Will Kiss&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;By Eduardo Santiago &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Amid the debate over immigration, a novel that reminds us of the multiplicity of real-life meanings encompassed by that term (Back Bay, $13.99).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The Bystander: John F. Kennedy and the Struggle for Black Equality&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;By Nick Bryant &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;An incisive analysis of JFK's record on race and civil rights. (Perseus, $29.95).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="tagline"&gt;Selected from books recently reviewed in the Globe. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</myarticlebody>

